1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:14,100
 Ok,I think we can start.Welcome to this second lecture in the series on monetary revolutions.

2
00:00:14,100 --> 00:00:29,800
 Tonight we are very fortunate to have a top expert on digital finance to talk to us about

3
00:00:29,800 --> 00:00:42,800
 a proto-Central Bank of Amsterdam.This is a private bank that later evolved into Central Bank

4
00:00:42,800 --> 00:00:55,800
 of the Netherlands and it has many interesting links to what central banks are doing today

5
00:00:55,800 --> 00:01:06,800
 and are concerned about today.Jon is heading the Innovation and Digital Economy Unit at the Bank

6
00:01:06,800 --> 00:01:15,800
 for International Settlement in Basel.He is incredibly productive.I just looked at the BIS website.This

7
00:01:15,800 --> 00:01:24,800
 year alone he has published nine different papers internally and I am sure many of them

8
00:01:24,800 --> 00:01:29,800
 will end up in top publications like the one that he will discuss today that was published

9
00:01:29,800 --> 00:01:43,800
 in Journal of Political Economy.John has also worked at the BIS office for the Americas in Mexico City

10
00:01:43,800 --> 00:01:55,800
 and before that he was in the BIS as well working at the Financial Stability Board and prior to

11
00:01:55,800 --> 00:02:04,800
 coming to the BIS he had engagements in academia in the Netherlands as well as in Dutch Central Bank

12
00:02:04,800 --> 00:02:15,800
 and the private sector in Germany.So without further ado John please tell us what was so interesting about the Bank of Amsterdam.

13
00:02:15,800 --> 00:02:26,800
 Thank you. Thanks so much Dubravko and thanks everyone for taking part and being here today tonight.

14
00:02:26,800 --> 00:02:35,800
 I was very happy about the invitation to this.I understood that Dubravko has been involved now with the

15
00:02:35,800 --> 00:02:44,800
 Croatia National Bank and with the museum and I was going to note that I am a regular visitor of money museums around the world.

16
00:02:44,800 --> 00:02:51,800
 My wife often gives me a hard time about that for being a boring central banker who likes to learn about money even in my free time.

17
00:02:51,800 --> 00:02:59,800
 So I've visited money museums in Canada, Finland, Mexico, Morocco, the Netherlands, but I've not yet been to Monatera.

18
00:02:59,800 --> 00:03:09,800
 So I hope that in the future on a visit to Croatia I'll have the chance and of course I'm very glad to take part in this discussion.

19
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:18,800
 So as Dubravko mentioned I'll be presenting today from a paper that is joint work with Vilko Bolt, Hünsong Shin and Peter Wirtz.

20
00:03:18,800 --> 00:03:28,800
 It's called The Bank of Amsterdam and the Limits of Fiat Money and this is part of a broader research agenda looking at how money is changing in the digital age

21
00:03:28,800 --> 00:03:33,800
 and about the institutions underpinning money including central banks.

22
00:03:33,800 --> 00:03:38,800
 So you'll see on the cover slide that money has changed a lot over the years.

23
00:03:38,800 --> 00:03:47,800
 You have the transition from Kauri shells and Lydian coins through the first Chinese paper money, English tally sticks, stone coins of Yap,

24
00:03:47,800 --> 00:03:57,800
 copper money and the like all the way up through modern ATMs, card readers and the new interfaces on smartphones.

25
00:03:57,800 --> 00:04:03,800
 Now the Bank of Amsterdam played a very important role in this transition of money through the years.

26
00:04:03,800 --> 00:04:14,800
 You'll see a paper ledger toward the middle of the cover slide and that is actually a specific record from the ledgers used like those at the bank.

27
00:04:14,800 --> 00:04:26,800
 And what we discussed in the paper is that the bank was also a predecessor of many of today's institutions like central banks as well as, if you will, today's stable coins.

28
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:33,800
 So there are deeper lessons for the limits of fiat money and I'll discuss what I mean in just a moment.

29
00:04:33,800 --> 00:04:38,800
 So here's the roadmap of what I'll be talking about today.

30
00:04:38,800 --> 00:04:44,800
 I'll start by describing our interest in the Bank of Amsterdam and why we see it as an early stable coin.

31
00:04:44,800 --> 00:04:46,800
 I'll talk about what I mean by that.

32
00:04:46,800 --> 00:05:01,800
 I'll then talk about how the bank evolved over time, moving from a rigid to a more elastic structure and fulfilling many of the functions that a modern central bank fulfills, including providing settlement liquidity and serving as a lender of last resort.

33
00:05:01,800 --> 00:05:18,800
 Then importantly, I'll talk about the bank's downfall in the late 18th and early 19th century and what it tells us for the limits of fiat money and the constraints that central banks may face in the 21st century.

34
00:05:18,800 --> 00:05:22,800
 So I'll conclude with a few lessons for the digital age.

35
00:05:22,800 --> 00:05:32,800
 John, could you please try to speak up? Because back of the room cannot hear you. I'm sorry, but we don't have a very good...

36
00:05:32,800 --> 00:05:42,800
 Okay, no problem. I'll aim to speak a little bit louder and if there's any problems in being audible, then just let me know and I will speak louder. No problem.

37
00:05:42,800 --> 00:05:46,800
 Okay, so let's start with the bank itself.

38
00:05:46,800 --> 00:06:00,800
 The Bank of Amsterdam was founded in 1609 and it was a precursor of modern central banks. It's often considered the first public Giro Bank that became, you know, a central bank later on.

39
00:06:00,800 --> 00:06:09,800
 And you can see here from the Dutch Golden Age, this is a painting of the headquarters of the Bank of Amsterdam on the main square, Dam Square in Amsterdam.

40
00:06:09,800 --> 00:06:26,800
 Today, this building is still there. It is the Royal Palace in Amsterdam, but up until the Napoleonic period, this was the City Hall and the Bank of Amsterdam was actually headquartered in City Hall and it was there as a public institution.

41
00:06:26,800 --> 00:06:38,800
 So it was founded by the city authorities with private shareholders, as Zubravko mentioned, with an explicit mandate to check the confusion of coin, as it was called.

42
00:06:38,800 --> 00:06:49,800
 So the idea was that there were a lot of circulating trade coins in those days, different metal coins, primarily silver, some golden coins that were used in international commerce.

43
00:06:49,800 --> 00:07:04,800
 They often were of differing quality, they circulated different exchange rates and the bank was instituted to try to bring some uniformity and to reduce some of that confusion in the monetary system.

44
00:07:06,800 --> 00:07:12,800
 It was modeled on similar institutions in Venice, Rome, Genoa, and Naples.

45
00:07:12,800 --> 00:07:26,800
 And interestingly, the bank itself was also an inspiration to Stockholm's Banco, which was the predecessor of the English Rijksbank, founded in 1664, and to the Bank of England, founded in 1694.

46
00:07:26,800 --> 00:07:34,800
 Of course, the Bank of England was founded by William Orange, who himself came from the Netherlands and was intimately familiar with the Bank of Amsterdam.

47
00:07:34,800 --> 00:07:45,800
 And so I think that's an important link between the Dutch Republic and then, of course, a very well known prominent central bank that many of us have interacted with today.

48
00:07:49,800 --> 00:07:54,800
 If you look at its early balance sheet, it had a very simple structure.

49
00:07:54,800 --> 00:08:05,800
 So on the asset side, it held primarily metal coins, so silver coins from the New World, particularly Spanish silver coins, and to a lesser extent gold.

50
00:08:05,800 --> 00:08:12,800
 And customers could physically deposit their coins with the bank and receive an assurance of their quality.

51
00:08:12,800 --> 00:08:20,800
 On the liability side, it had accounts by merchants, up to 3,000 merchants at its peak.

52
00:08:20,800 --> 00:08:25,800
 And its first seven decades, it's what we might call a rigid stable coin.

53
00:08:25,800 --> 00:08:30,800
 Its balances were determined passively by the flow of deposits in and out.

54
00:08:30,800 --> 00:08:39,800
 Whenever someone would bring coins to the bank, they would then be credited with a balance in bank guilders on the liability side of the balance sheet.

55
00:08:39,800 --> 00:08:43,800
 And if they wanted to redeem their coins, they could do that.

56
00:08:43,800 --> 00:08:46,800
 And then the balance sheet would shrink accordingly.

57
00:08:46,800 --> 00:08:52,800
 Still, the bank served a very important function, just without much discretion over its balance sheet.

58
00:08:52,800 --> 00:09:00,800
 It had this rigid structure and the size of the balances was determined primarily by client development.

59
00:09:00,800 --> 00:09:06,800
 It did enjoy an impeccable reputation.

60
00:09:06,800 --> 00:09:12,800
 For instance, in The Wealth of Nations, Adam Smith devotes several pages to the bank.

61
00:09:12,800 --> 00:09:17,800
 And the whole passage is great, but I'll just quote one part of it.

62
00:09:17,800 --> 00:09:25,800
 In Amsterdam, however, no point of faith is better established than that for every guilder circulated as bank money.

63
00:09:25,800 --> 00:09:31,800
 There is a correspondent guilder in gold or silver to be found in the treasure of the bank.

64
00:09:31,800 --> 00:09:36,800
 He went on to say the governing burgomasters ensure that it is so.

65
00:09:36,800 --> 00:09:42,800
 And in this sober and religious country, oaths are not taken in vain.

66
00:09:42,800 --> 00:09:44,800
 So in other words, people keep their promises.

67
00:09:44,800 --> 00:09:57,800
 They can be certain that one guilder held at the bank corresponds to a guilder in coins kept in reserve.

68
00:09:57,800 --> 00:10:00,800
 And there are some other great stories.

69
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:12,800
 I won't go into them, but Voltaire also has a very memorable description of the bank and of the panic of 1672 when, you know, the bank was able to maintain this reputation.

70
00:10:12,800 --> 00:10:23,800
 So it was really known for being well run for having, you know, a one to one backing at all times.

71
00:10:23,800 --> 00:10:40,800
 But perhaps somewhat ironically, just around the time that Adam Smith was writing that was when things the bank actually started to diverge from that one to one backing for reasons that I'll talk about in just a moment.

72
00:10:40,800 --> 00:10:56,800
 Now, because of this high reputation and, you know, the function that the bank fulfilled in running a payment system, the bank guilders actually traded at a premium to the coins.

73
00:10:56,800 --> 00:11:07,800
 So if you had one bank guilder in your account at the Bank of Amsterdam, then on average, that was worth about 5% more than having a coin, a metal guilder in your pocket.

74
00:11:07,800 --> 00:11:12,800
 And this premium can be tracked over time.

75
00:11:12,800 --> 00:11:21,800
 There's very good data going back to the late 17th century about the Dutch agio, it's called.

76
00:11:21,800 --> 00:11:24,800
 And for the most part, this fluctuated around 5%.

77
00:11:24,800 --> 00:11:26,800
 So it was pretty stable.

78
00:11:26,800 --> 00:11:29,800
 And you can see this is a gauge of trust in the bank.

79
00:11:29,800 --> 00:11:35,800
 And so you can see up in Adam Smith's time that's shown here around 1776.

80
00:11:35,800 --> 00:11:37,800
 It was remarkably stable.

81
00:11:37,800 --> 00:11:46,800
 So this gauge of trust, you know, was a useful measure for looking at trust overall.

82
00:11:46,800 --> 00:11:56,800
 And you can see that it actually even picked up a little bit during the crisis of 1762, which I'll talk about in a little bit as well.

83
00:11:56,800 --> 00:12:08,800
 But then there comes a period where the agio starts to erode and where, as I'll talk about later, it finally breaks into negative territory where people lost their trust in the bank.

84
00:12:08,800 --> 00:12:12,800
 And then, you know, it took quite a while to recover from that.

85
00:12:12,800 --> 00:12:19,800
 And that was what really led to the bank's downfall and its eventual replacement with space modern central bank.

86
00:12:19,800 --> 00:12:37,800
 So what happened? Why is it that this very simple, you know, rigid structure gave way to a very different structure and eventually a breakdown entirely of the functioning of the bank?

87
00:12:37,800 --> 00:12:44,800
 So to understand that, we have to go to the next chapter in the story.

88
00:12:44,800 --> 00:12:49,800
 And the question is, was full backing really optimal and was that really the solution?

89
00:12:49,800 --> 00:12:52,800
 The reality was a little bit more complex than what we're discussing before.

90
00:12:52,800 --> 00:13:03,800
 And as we would argue, full backing alone would not have been sufficient for the bank to play the important global role that it ultimately did.

91
00:13:03,800 --> 00:13:13,800
 So really, this change happened in the late 17th century already from 1683 onward, the bank moved toward this more elastic structure.

92
00:13:13,800 --> 00:13:20,800
 There was a new system, the receipts system and explicit money creation.

93
00:13:20,800 --> 00:13:31,800
 So the way that this happened, starting in 1683, the bank introduced something, a new innovation.

94
00:13:31,800 --> 00:13:42,800
 It suspended convertibility, creating a gap between so-called current guilders, the coins that circulated in daily use and bank guilders, the accounts at the bank.

95
00:13:42,800 --> 00:13:49,800
 As before, the public could still deposit their metal coins with the bank through the receipt system.

96
00:13:49,800 --> 00:13:53,800
 They would receive a receipt and could redeem the coins after a period of six months.

97
00:13:53,800 --> 00:14:03,800
 So the coins that were held with receipts were encumbered and the deposits that matched with those coins were called encumbered deposits.

98
00:14:03,800 --> 00:14:09,800
 But on top of that, the bank could also buy and sell coins freely in the market.

99
00:14:09,800 --> 00:14:12,800
 You can see that as an early form of open market operations.

100
00:14:12,800 --> 00:14:19,800
 And these coins, as well as the deposits that were created through purchases, were under the discretion of the bank.

101
00:14:19,800 --> 00:14:20,800
 They were unencumbered.

102
00:14:20,800 --> 00:14:25,800
 They weren't promised to any specific holder of bank builders.

103
00:14:25,800 --> 00:14:40,800
 So one could argue, as researchers like Stephen Quinn and Will Roberts have, that this policy change was the genesis of modern fiat money.

104
00:14:40,800 --> 00:14:45,800
 The bank, after this change, started to fulfill the functions of a proto-central bank.

105
00:14:45,800 --> 00:14:47,800
 It did so in three main ways.

106
00:14:47,800 --> 00:14:59,800
 First, it tried to keep the Agio stable around 5% on average through monetary operations, buying and selling coins whenever the Agio started to diverge from this target.

107
00:14:59,800 --> 00:15:04,800
 Second, it adjusted the money stock for settlement liquidity in the wholesale payment system.

108
00:15:04,800 --> 00:15:14,800
 So especially for these transactions between those 3,000 merchants and the Dutch East India Company and other major businesses that I'll talk about.

109
00:15:14,800 --> 00:15:19,800
 Finally, it functioned as a lender of last resort in times of stress.

110
00:15:19,800 --> 00:15:23,800
 So let me just show some evidence for what I'm talking about.

111
00:15:23,800 --> 00:15:36,800
 First, regarding the maintenance of a stable Agio, the bank would frequently purchase precious precious metal whenever there was a shock in the Agio.

112
00:15:36,800 --> 00:15:52,800
 So if the Agio went up and the difference between bank builders and current builders was getting too large, then the bank could buy metal coins,

113
00:15:52,800 --> 00:15:56,800
 and then pushing down the difference between the two.

114
00:15:56,800 --> 00:16:00,800
 And that's a little bit like modern central banks do to maintain a policy target.

115
00:16:00,800 --> 00:16:03,800
 They have operations like this and you can actually see this.

116
00:16:03,800 --> 00:16:14,800
 We do some calculations, impulse response function similar to what Quinn and Roberts do for the period 1736 to 1775.

117
00:16:14,800 --> 00:16:22,800
 We really see in practice these purchases in response to positive shocks of the Agio and it was symmetric.

118
00:16:22,800 --> 00:16:36,800
 So when the Agio fell, they would then sell coins, reduce the size of the balance sheet, make bank guilders more scarce relative to current guilders, and that in turn would push up the Agio.

119
00:16:36,800 --> 00:16:46,800
 So they did this actively and with discretion in order to maintain a stable Agio.

120
00:16:46,800 --> 00:16:54,800
 Second, I'm going to talk about the role in settlement liquidity, but I'm going to need to explain a little bit more about the structure of the financial sector at the time to do so.

121
00:16:54,800 --> 00:17:04,800
 So, as I'll talk about more, one of the largest entities in the local economy at the time was the Dutch East India Company, which was known by its Dutch acronym VOC.

122
00:17:04,800 --> 00:17:16,800
 And there are wonderful paintings, you know, if you look at the city archives or the Rijksmuseum in Amsterdam.

123
00:17:16,800 --> 00:17:32,800
 Here's, you know, one painting of a ship of the VOC and they were active around the world trading in colonies and, you know, finance through, through stock, through as a joint stock company.

124
00:17:32,800 --> 00:17:44,800
 So the VOC traded in outposts across Asia, in particularly in Gaal, in today's Sri Lanka, and in Batavia, today's Jakarta in Indonesia.

125
00:17:44,800 --> 00:17:55,800
 And you can see that there are these various trade networks, so sea routes that connect the different trading ports of the day with Cape Town and Amsterdam.

126
00:17:55,800 --> 00:18:04,800
 And they traded spices, sugar, cloth, as well as those coins, silver coins that I talked about.

127
00:18:04,800 --> 00:18:11,800
 And it tended to be that they would depart and return in a seasonal pattern.

128
00:18:11,800 --> 00:18:16,800
 So we actually have the digitized ship logs from the Dutch East India Company.

129
00:18:16,800 --> 00:18:24,800
 And you can see that the departures from Europe tended to happen toward the end of the year.

130
00:18:24,800 --> 00:18:33,800
 And so around November, December, January, most frequently in some occasions, also August, September, October.

131
00:18:33,800 --> 00:18:41,800
 They would then go out, trade in the colonies and return usually around May and June, sometimes July.

132
00:18:41,800 --> 00:18:46,800
 And that's shown in the red bars here.

133
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:51,800
 Between their departure and their arrival, there was a lack of money in the payment system.

134
00:18:51,800 --> 00:18:56,800
 That could result in gridlock, much like the differences in intraday credit that we know of today.

135
00:18:56,800 --> 00:19:03,800
 There would be the outgoing payments, but there wouldn't yet be the incoming payments in order to provide sufficient liquidity.

136
00:19:03,800 --> 00:19:09,800
 So the bank played a very important role in smoothing this, providing settlement liquidity in the system.

137
00:19:09,800 --> 00:19:12,800
 And they did that through loans.

138
00:19:12,800 --> 00:19:16,800
 So you can see this in the unencumbered accounts.

139
00:19:16,800 --> 00:19:25,800
 They created these on a balance sheet in order to grant credit to the VOC as the largest commercial client of the day.

140
00:19:25,800 --> 00:19:35,800
 And there was a very clear correlation between the change in Dutch East India loan companies, shown on the x-axis,

141
00:19:35,800 --> 00:19:41,800
 and the changes in unencumbered accounts in millions of guilders, shown on the y-axis.

142
00:19:41,800 --> 00:19:44,800
 So essentially they were diverging from this one-to-one backing.

143
00:19:44,800 --> 00:19:56,800
 Instead of having one metal coin to back each bank gilder in deposits, there were some occasions where they could lend to the VOC for a period of a few months.

144
00:19:56,800 --> 00:19:57,800
 They'd be paid back again.

145
00:19:57,800 --> 00:20:02,800
 And that would help to keep the payment system functioning smoothly in the interim.

146
00:20:02,800 --> 00:20:05,800
 And strictly speaking, that wasn't allowed under their mandate.

147
00:20:05,800 --> 00:20:09,800
 But in practice, it did allow them to play this very important role.

148
00:20:09,800 --> 00:20:16,800
 And it probably helped Amsterdam to maintain its position as a global financial center.

149
00:20:16,800 --> 00:20:24,800
 Finally, I'm going to talk about the role the Bank of Amsterdam played as a lender of last resort, that third function.

150
00:20:24,800 --> 00:20:31,800
 And this was particularly clear in the panic of 1762 and three.

151
00:20:31,800 --> 00:20:46,800
 So in this year, and this has been written about at length by Jun Song Shin and Isabel Schnabel, for instance, there was a panic that affected the market for bills of trade.

152
00:20:46,800 --> 00:20:58,800
 And I won't go into the details, but there were bills of trade that linked together the trading posts of Amsterdam, as well as Prussia at the time, the emerging market.

153
00:20:58,800 --> 00:21:03,800
 And there was a sudden drying up of credit across this very long chain.

154
00:21:03,800 --> 00:21:11,800
 And so the bank was needed to step in and to credit the accounts of various borrowers.

155
00:21:11,800 --> 00:21:14,800
 So it accepted a very large inflow of deposits.

156
00:21:14,800 --> 00:21:21,800
 It changed its collateral framework to actually allow for collateralized lending to credit worthy borrowers.

157
00:21:21,800 --> 00:21:27,800
 They started accepting different types of collateral additional coins that you hadn't accepted before.

158
00:21:27,800 --> 00:21:34,800
 And this helped to smooth the panic and the shocks to the payment system.

159
00:21:34,800 --> 00:21:39,800
 And it cemented the role of Amsterdam as an important financial center after 1763.

160
00:21:40,800 --> 00:21:56,800
 And if you would like, I mean, you can draw a very clear parallel with the role that central banks played more recently, for instance, in the global financial crisis or even in the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020.

161
00:21:56,800 --> 00:22:03,800
 The Fed, in this case, also accepted more deposits, accepted different forms, types of collateral.

162
00:22:03,800 --> 00:22:10,800
 And, you know, that helps to smooth the shocks to the payment system during 2020.

163
00:22:10,800 --> 00:22:26,800
 So if we take a very long view, this is, you know, the asset side of the Bank of Amsterdam balance sheets over its full lifespan from 1609 all the way up till 1820.

164
00:22:26,800 --> 00:22:31,800
 You can see that, you know, over the majority of this period, this worked very well.

165
00:22:31,800 --> 00:22:42,800
 Despite the proto central bank operations, the role in maintaining the agio and settlement liquidity and functioning as a lender of last resort.

166
00:22:42,800 --> 00:22:46,800
 For the most part, bank builders remained backed by metal stock.

167
00:22:46,800 --> 00:22:47,800
 It was shown here in red.

168
00:22:47,800 --> 00:22:54,800
 There were some divergence, for instance, in the 1730s and 1740s, but this didn't really threaten the bank's solidity.

169
00:22:54,800 --> 00:23:06,800
 It's only at the end of the 18th century and in particular after 1780 that we see this striking divergence from full backing and, you know, ultimately the bank's downfall.

170
00:23:06,800 --> 00:23:11,800
 So what happened, I'll now discuss that in a little bit more depth.

171
00:23:11,800 --> 00:23:24,800
 So the VOC, as I mentioned, was an extremely important player in the economy of the Netherlands and of Amsterdam, as well as, you know, the functioning of the bank and the financial system in Amsterdam.

172
00:23:24,800 --> 00:23:32,800
 And the immediate trigger for the banks downfall was the fourth Anglo-Dutch war of 1780 to 1784.

173
00:23:32,800 --> 00:23:43,800
 As you can tell, there had been other wars with England previously, but in this particular war, the English and Dutch fought in European, Asian and African waters.

174
00:23:43,800 --> 00:23:49,800
 The Dutch lost quite a few ships in battle, including ships of the VOC.

175
00:23:49,800 --> 00:23:53,800
 This was around the same time, by the way, as the American Revolution.

176
00:23:53,800 --> 00:24:02,800
 You know, there was a large global conflagration between the UK, France, the Netherlands, Spain.

177
00:24:02,800 --> 00:24:07,800
 And so a number of different theaters of war.

178
00:24:07,800 --> 00:24:13,800
 But what was important for the purposes of the discussion today is that quite a few ships were lost.

179
00:24:13,800 --> 00:24:18,800
 Ships were sunk given these seaborne battles.

180
00:24:18,800 --> 00:24:21,800
 This is visible in trade statistics.

181
00:24:21,800 --> 00:24:25,800
 So you can see here that in 1780, trade dropped by nearly three quarters.

182
00:24:25,800 --> 00:24:29,800
 Ships that had been kitted out for the voyage to Asia didn't return.

183
00:24:29,800 --> 00:24:32,800
 And again, you can see this in the digitized ships logs.

184
00:24:32,800 --> 00:24:38,800
 There's lots of very specific cases of ships that didn't make the journey back to Amsterdam.

185
00:24:38,800 --> 00:24:44,800
 So the bank had initially lent to the VOC on a short term basis, primarily for settlement liquidity.

186
00:24:44,800 --> 00:24:55,800
 But now it had to do so on a much larger scale, really to bail out the VOC, which was an important employer, an important economic entity in that time.

187
00:24:55,800 --> 00:25:00,800
 And trust in the bank, as measured by the agio, started to suffer.

188
00:25:00,800 --> 00:25:06,800
 So you can see here that in 1780, there was already a few shocks.

189
00:25:06,800 --> 00:25:10,800
 The bank was able to largely hide what they were doing, and it didn't come to light.

190
00:25:10,800 --> 00:25:13,800
 In 1782, it became more clear.

191
00:25:13,800 --> 00:25:19,800
 The bank steadily ramped up its lending, but it was still able to maintain trust.

192
00:25:19,800 --> 00:25:24,800
 It was only in 1790 that the agio turns negative for the first time.

193
00:25:24,800 --> 00:25:32,800
 It was finally in 1795, actually from the French Revolutionary Army, the forces of Napoleon entered the Netherlands,

194
00:25:32,800 --> 00:25:37,800
 that the new authorities instructed that the full books be made public.

195
00:25:37,800 --> 00:25:46,800
 And then it became clear that the bank was really in over its neck to, with credit to the VOC, trust evaporated.

196
00:25:46,800 --> 00:25:48,800
 The agio went sharply negative.

197
00:25:48,800 --> 00:25:55,800
 And the bank lived on, but in a very diminished form, up until the early 19th century.

198
00:25:55,800 --> 00:26:08,800
 In 1814, the new king, who came in to replace Napoleon's little brother, founded the modern central bank, the Netherlands Bank,

199
00:26:08,800 --> 00:26:11,800
 and then eventually closed the Bank of Amsterdam.

200
00:26:11,800 --> 00:26:15,800
 And that's why the Netherlands, despite, you know, of course, the long history with the Bank of Amsterdam

201
00:26:15,800 --> 00:26:24,800
 and a long history of central banking, now has a central bank that was only founded in 1814 rather than the 1609.

202
00:26:24,800 --> 00:26:30,800
 So there are a lot of lessons from this episode for debates today.

203
00:26:30,800 --> 00:26:34,800
 And so I'd like to just briefly touch on two of these now.

204
00:26:34,800 --> 00:26:49,800
 First of all, in our paper, we draw this lesson that there is a unique breakpoint where the negative equity of a central bank and asset illiquidity can erode trust in fiat money.

205
00:26:49,800 --> 00:26:55,800
 I haven't shown our formal model today, but suffice it to say that, you know, you can solve for this breakpoint.

206
00:26:55,800 --> 00:27:07,800
 And so even though modern central banks may lend, you know, to governments, for instance, may have collateral frameworks for lending as lender of last resort to financial institutions.

207
00:27:07,800 --> 00:27:09,800
 Generally, that goes well.

208
00:27:09,800 --> 00:27:12,800
 Generally, we aren't too worried about the equity position of central banks.

209
00:27:12,800 --> 00:27:17,800
 Central banks can operate with negative equity at times, but there is a point at which you can go too far.

210
00:27:17,800 --> 00:27:21,800
 There is a breakpoint, and if that happens, then trust and money can break down.

211
00:27:21,800 --> 00:27:29,800
 And of course, it's very important to stay away from that breakpoint so as not to risk that trust and money erodes as well.

212
00:27:29,800 --> 00:27:39,800
 And second, for a central bank to play its important role in the economy, the fiscal backing of the sovereign and its fiscal sustainability are essential.

213
00:27:39,800 --> 00:27:47,800
 The bank at the time didn't have full fiscal backing from the city authorities, and that meant when it did make losses, it wasn't able to recover.

214
00:27:47,800 --> 00:27:56,800
 Ultimately, the bank had to give way to this new institution that had lots of bank and that's to a central bank that's operated more successfully for the two centuries since.

215
00:27:56,800 --> 00:28:06,800
 But now, of course, in the euro area, there are explicit requirements that if a central bank has negative equity, it must be recapitalized by the government.

216
00:28:06,800 --> 00:28:09,800
 And this explains why this might be so important.

217
00:28:09,800 --> 00:28:15,800
 But if you take away one thing from this historical discussion, it's I think that should be the following.

218
00:28:15,800 --> 00:28:21,800
 There is a reason that we have national central banks and sovereign fiat currencies in nearly every country in the world today.

219
00:28:21,800 --> 00:28:27,800
 We've tried through trial and error, including episodes like this one, with different institutions.

220
00:28:27,800 --> 00:28:32,800
 But we found that this institutional innovation of central banks has proven remarkably robust.

221
00:28:32,800 --> 00:28:37,800
 And today in the digital era, there are opportunities to improve the payment system and the functions of money.

222
00:28:37,800 --> 00:28:43,800
 But, you know, there shouldn't be a role for changing the governance that underpins money.

223
00:28:43,800 --> 00:28:49,800
 Having solid central banks with sound finances remains as important as ever.

